---
// /packages/engines — Flagship page for Ikenga engine adapters.
// Claude Code = default (built-in). Gemini + Codex = pluggable adapters.
// All require the Ikenga shell; these are NOT standalone skills.
// Draft: plans/launch/drafts/pkg-page-engines.md
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import FeaturePage from '../../components/FeaturePage.astro';
import Button from '../../components/Button.astro';
import BrandIcon from '../../components/BrandIcon.astro';
import InstallBlock from '../../components/InstallBlock.astro';
---

<Layout
	title="Engines — Claude Code, wired in · Ikenga"
	description="Claude Code is the default engine, fully wired. Gemini CLI and Codex CLI are pluggable adapters — install either alongside it, same setup, same shell. Your skills and MCP servers fan out to each without duplication."
	canonical="https://ikenga.dev/packages/engines"
>
	<FeaturePage
		eyebrow="Engine pkgs · Apache-2.0"
		title={`Claude Code, wired in`}
		lede="Claude Code is the default engine, fully wired. Gemini CLI and Codex CLI are pluggable adapters — install either alongside it, swap with a click."
		problem="An engine is the AI backend that drives your workspace. Ikenga leads with Claude Code: it wraps the claude CLI you already have, parses its streaming output, and wires it into the shell's session layer — persistence, resume, and the cockpit's config surface all work out of the box. Gemini CLI and Codex CLI follow the same manifest-and-adapter pattern. One workspace, your choice of backend."
		worksWith="Requires the Ikenga shell. Claude Code is active as soon as you install the shell — no extra step."
		docsHref="/docs/engines"
		catalogHref="/packages"
	>

		<!-- Beat 1: The problem it removes — copy-only (no available screenshot) -->
		<section class="sk-section">
			<div class="sk-wrap">
				<h2 class="sk-h2">The problem it removes</h2>
				<p class="sk-body">
					Most setups are engine-specific by accident. Your Claude Code skills are in
					<code>~/.claude/skills/</code>. Your Gemini config is somewhere else. Your Codex
					prompts are somewhere else again. When you want to compare two backends on the
					same task, you're reconfiguring from scratch. When Claude releases a new model,
					you update one place; when you try Gemini, you rebuild.
				</p>
				<p class="sk-body">
					Ikenga's engine layer removes that accident. Each engine is a manifest-declared
					pkg. Your skills, commands, and MCP servers install once and are available to
					all of them. Swapping backends for a thread is a two-click popover, not a
					config migration.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Beat 2: Claude Code is the default, fully wired — copy-only (no screenshot) -->
		<section class="sk-section">
			<div class="sk-wrap">
				<h2 class="sk-h2">Claude Code is the default, <em>fully wired</em></h2>
				<p class="sk-body">
					Claude Code (<code>com.ikenga.engine-claude-code</code>) ships as the built-in
					engine pkg — your Chi, the reasoning layer at the heart of every thread. It
					spawns your local <code>claude</code> binary, parses its stream-json output
					through a Rust translator, and produces normalized <code>SessionUpdate</code>
					envelopes on the shell's session wire. Every shell feature — session
					persistence, resume (<code>claude --resume &lt;id&gt;</code>), the cockpit's
					skills/commands/MCP manager, thinking, tool use, MCP — is exercised through
					this path.
				</p>
				<p class="sk-body">
					No separate account required. Auth is <code>claude login</code> or
					<code>ANTHROPIC_API_KEY</code> — whichever you already use in the terminal.
				</p>
				<div class="eg-caps">
					<h3 class="eg-caps__head">Capabilities — Claude Code adapter</h3>
					<table class="eg-table">
						<thead>
							<tr>
								<th>Capability</th>
								<th>Supported</th>
							</tr>
						</thead>
						<tbody>
							<tr><td>Streaming</td><td class="eg-check">✓</td></tr>
							<tr><td>Tool use</td><td class="eg-check">✓</td></tr>
							<tr><td>Thinking</td><td class="eg-check">✓</td></tr>
							<tr><td>Artifacts</td><td class="eg-check">✓</td></tr>
							<tr><td>File attachments</td><td class="eg-check">✓</td></tr>
							<tr><td>Image input</td><td class="eg-check">✓</td></tr>
							<tr><td>Slash commands</td><td class="eg-check">✓</td></tr>
							<tr><td>Model switching</td><td class="eg-check">✓</td></tr>
							<tr><td>Prompt caching</td><td class="eg-check">✓</td></tr>
							<tr><td>Agentic tools</td><td class="eg-check">✓</td></tr>
							<tr><td>MCP</td><td class="eg-check">✓</td></tr>
							<tr><td>Session resume</td><td class="eg-check">✓</td></tr>
						</tbody>
					</table>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Beat 3: Gemini and Codex as pluggable adapters — copy-only (no screenshot) -->
		<section class="sk-section">
			<div class="sk-wrap">
				<h2 class="sk-h2">Gemini and Codex as pluggable adapters</h2>
				<p class="sk-body">
					Gemini CLI (<code>com.ikenga.engine-gemini</code>) and Codex CLI
					(<code>com.ikenga.engine-codex</code>) follow the same manifest-and-adapter
					pattern. Both are separately installable engine pkgs — add them from the
					shell's package manager or directly via the <code>ikenga</code> CLI. Install
					one or both alongside Claude Code; remove either without touching anything
					else.
				</p>
				<p class="sk-body">
					The Gemini adapter uses an ACP passthrough: it spawns <code>gemini</code> and
					proxies its JSON-RPC 2.0 NDJSON protocol bidirectionally. The Codex adapter
					uses a custom stream adapter: it parses <code>codex exec --json</code> output
					into the shell's normalized envelopes. Either way the frontend sees the same
					wire — one session shape, one chat UI, regardless of which engine is active.
				</p>
				<p class="sk-body">
					Each adapter's manifest declares an <strong>onboarding block</strong>: which
					vault keys it needs (<code>GEMINI_API_KEY</code>, <code>OPENAI_API_KEY</code>),
					the auth command to copy, and a docs link. The first-run wizard surfaces this
					before you can start a thread, so auth never breaks silently.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Beat 4: Per-turn engine and model switching — copy-only (no screenshot) -->
		<section class="sk-section">
			<div class="sk-wrap">
				<h2 class="sk-h2">Per-turn engine and model switching</h2>
				<p class="sk-body">
					A chat thread is created with one engine and stays pinned to it — sessions
					resume against the same backend they were started on. But within a thread,
					the composer lets you swap the engine and model <strong>per turn</strong>: a
					single send can route to a different backend without changing the thread. The
					picker is a two-level Engine → Model popover, always visible in the composer.
				</p>
				<p class="sk-body">
					This is useful for comparison: start a thread with Claude Code, send the same
					prompt to Gemini in the next turn, see both responses in the same history. No
					context copy-paste, no tab-switching.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Beat 5: Engines are pkgs — copy-only (no screenshot) -->
		<section class="sk-section">
			<div class="sk-wrap">
				<h2 class="sk-h2">Engines are pkgs — the architecture is open</h2>
				<p class="sk-body">
					Every engine adapter is a standard Ikenga pkg. It declares a
					<code>kind: "engine"</code> manifest, a capability matrix the UI reads to
					enable or disable features per backend, and the onboarding metadata for the
					auth wizard. Installing or removing an engine is the same operation as
					installing or removing any other pkg.
				</p>
				<p class="sk-body">
					Adding a brand-new engine today requires both a manifest pkg in
					<code>ikenga-pkgs</code> and a Rust adapter in the shell — it is not yet a
					pure drop-in. The <code>Engine</code> interface in
					<code>@ikenga/contract</code> is the direction of travel; treat it as
					forward-looking until the purely-pkg-side adapter path lands.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Available engines table -->
		<section class="sk-section">
			<div class="sk-wrap">
				<h2 class="sk-h2">Available engines</h2>
				<p class="sk-body">
					Each engine requires its CLI binary on your <code>$PATH</code>. The shell
					resolves the binary path from a configurable setting
					(<code>claude_binary</code>, <code>gemini_binary</code>,
					<code>codex_binary</code>) so non-default install locations work.
				</p>
				<div class="eg-caps">
					<table class="eg-table">
						<thead>
							<tr>
								<th>Engine</th>
								<th>Pkg id</th>
								<th>Auth</th>
								<th>Default model</th>
							</tr>
						</thead>
						<tbody>
							<tr>
								<td><BrandIcon name="claude" /> <strong>Claude Code</strong></td>
								<td><code>com.ikenga.engine-claude-code</code></td>
								<td><code>claude login</code> / <code>ANTHROPIC_API_KEY</code></td>
								<td><code>claude-sonnet-4-6</code></td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td><BrandIcon name="gemini" /> <strong>Gemini CLI</strong></td>
								<td><code>com.ikenga.engine-gemini</code></td>
								<td><code>gemini auth</code> / <code>GEMINI_API_KEY</code></td>
								<td><code>gemini-2.0-flash</code></td>
							</tr>
							<tr>
								<td><BrandIcon name="codex" /> <strong>Codex CLI</strong></td>
								<td><code>com.ikenga.engine-codex</code></td>
								<td><code>codex login</code> / <code>OPENAI_API_KEY</code></td>
								<td><code>o4-mini</code></td>
							</tr>
						</tbody>
					</table>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Install -->
		<section class="sk-section" id="install">
			<div class="sk-wrap">
				<h2 class="sk-h2">Install</h2>
				<p class="sk-body">
					Claude Code is the built-in engine — it is active as soon as you install the
					Ikenga shell. No extra step.
				</p>
				<p class="sk-body">To add Gemini CLI or Codex CLI:</p>
				<div class="eg-installs">
					<InstallBlock cmd="ikenga add @ikenga/pkg-engine-gemini">
						<p class="sk-install__note">
							Requires the <strong>Ikenga shell</strong> and the
							<code>gemini</code> CLI on your <code>$PATH</code>.
							<a href="/#install">Get the shell →</a>
						</p>
					</InstallBlock>
					<InstallBlock cmd="ikenga add @ikenga/pkg-engine-codex">
						<p class="sk-install__note">
							Requires the <strong>Ikenga shell</strong> and the
							<code>codex</code> CLI on your <code>$PATH</code>.
						</p>
					</InstallBlock>
				</div>
				<p class="sk-body eg-license">
					Apache-2.0. <a href="https://github.com/Royalti-io/ikenga-pkgs/blob/main/LICENSE" rel="noopener noreferrer">Read it</a>.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- See also -->
		<section class="sk-section">
			<div class="sk-wrap">
				<h2 class="sk-h2">See also</h2>
				<div class="eg-links">
					<Button href="/packages" variant="ghost">All packages →</Button>
					<Button href="/docs/engines" variant="ghost">Engine reference docs →</Button>
					<Button href="https://github.com/Royalti-io/ikenga-pkgs" variant="ghost" rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub: royalti-io/ikenga-pkgs →</Button>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

	</FeaturePage>
</Layout>

<style>
	/* Capability / engines table */
	.eg-caps {
		margin-top: var(--space-5);
		overflow-x: auto;
	}
	.eg-caps__head {
		font-family: var(--site-font-mono);
		font-size: 0.8125rem;
		letter-spacing: 0.06em;
		text-transform: uppercase;
		color: var(--site-muted);
		margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);
	}
	.eg-table {
		width: 100%;
		border-collapse: collapse;
		font-size: 0.9375rem;
		color: var(--site-muted);
	}
	.eg-table th {
		font-family: var(--site-font-mono);
		font-size: 0.75rem;
		letter-spacing: 0.08em;
		text-transform: uppercase;
		color: var(--site-accent);
		text-align: left;
		padding: var(--space-2) var(--space-4) var(--space-2) 0;
		border-bottom: 1px solid var(--site-border);
	}
	.eg-table td {
		padding: var(--space-2) var(--space-4) var(--space-2) 0;
		border-bottom: 1px solid var(--site-border-soft);
		vertical-align: top;
	}
	.eg-table td code {
		font-family: var(--site-font-mono);
		font-size: 0.84rem;
		color: var(--site-accent);
		background: var(--site-accent-soft);
		padding: 1px 6px;
		border-radius: var(--radius-sm, 4px);
	}
	.eg-table td strong {
		color: var(--site-fg);
	}
	.eg-check {
		color: var(--site-accent);
		font-size: 1rem;
	}

	/* Two install blocks stacked with a gap */
	.eg-installs {
		display: grid;
		gap: var(--space-5);
		max-width: 36rem;
		margin-bottom: var(--space-5);
	}
	.eg-installs a {
		color: var(--site-accent);
		text-decoration: none;
	}
	.eg-installs a:hover {
		text-decoration: underline;
	}

	.eg-license {
		font-size: 0.9rem;
	}
	.eg-license a {
		color: var(--site-accent);
		text-decoration: none;
	}
	.eg-license a:hover {
		text-decoration: underline;
	}

	/* See-also button row */
	.eg-links {
		display: flex;
		gap: var(--space-3);
		flex-wrap: wrap;
	}

	/* Inline code in body text (not in .sk-body which uses .sk-body code rule) */
	code {
		font-family: var(--site-font-mono);
		font-size: 0.9em;
		color: var(--site-accent);
		background: var(--site-accent-soft);
		padding: 1px 6px;
		border-radius: var(--radius-sm, 4px);
	}
</style>
